      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Delapan Puluh Bersaudara',
        headingEn: 'The Eighty Brothers',
        body: '''Menurut Kojiki, catatan tertua mitologi Jepang yang disusun pada awal abad kedelapan, Okuninushi ('Tuan Agung Negeri') adalah yang termuda dari delapan puluh bersaudara yang disebut Yasogami. Karena ia bungsu dan berhati lembut, para kakaknya memperlakukannya seperti pelayan, memaksanya membawa kantong-kantong berat berisi barang bawaan mereka dalam setiap perjalanan. Suatu hari, seluruh delapan puluh bersaudara itu berangkat menuju tanah Inaba untuk melamar seorang putri cantik bernama Yakami-hime, dan masing-masing berharap dialah yang akan dipilihnya. Okuninushi dipaksa berjalan jauh di belakang rombongan, memikul beban barang-barang kakaknya, sehingga ia tiba paling akhir di setiap persinggahan. Perjalanan panjang menuju Inaba inilah yang membawanya melewati pesisir Cape Keta, tempat sebuah pertemuan tak terduga akan mengubah nasibnya selamanya dan mengungkap watak sejati yang membedakannya dari saudara-saudaranya yang congkak.''',
        bodyEn: '''According to the Kojiki, the oldest record of Japanese mythology compiled in the early eighth century, Okuninushi ('Great Lord of the Land') was the youngest of eighty brothers known as the Yasogami. Because he was the youngest and gentle of heart, his brothers treated him like a servant, forcing him to carry heavy sacks of their belongings on every journey. One day, all eighty brothers set out for the land of Inaba to court a beautiful princess named Yakami-hime, each hoping he would be the one chosen. Okuninushi was made to walk far behind the group, burdened with his brothers' baggage, so that he always arrived last at every stopping place. This long journey toward Inaba led him along the shore of Cape Keta, where an unexpected encounter would change his fate forever and reveal a true character that set him apart from his arrogant brothers.''',
