        body: '''Ketika Okuninushi akhirnya tiba di tempat itu, tertinggal jauh di belakang karena memikul seluruh barang bawaan kakak-kakaknya, ia menemukan kelinci itu masih menangis kesakitan di tepi pantai. Dengan penuh belas kasih ia bertanya apa yang terjadi, dan kelinci pun menceritakan seluruh kisahnya, termasuk nasihat kejam yang telah diberikan delapan puluh bersaudara sebelumnya. Okuninushi segera memberi petunjuk yang benar: ia menyuruh kelinci itu pergi ke muara sungai terdekat, mencuci tubuhnya dengan air tawar untuk membersihkan garam, lalu berguling-guling di atas serbuk sari bunga gama (kama, sejenis alang-alang), yang akan menempel pada lukanya dan menyembuhkannya. Kelinci mengikuti petunjuk itu dengan saksama, dan seketika kulitnya pulih sempurna seperti sedia kala. Berkat kesabaran mendengarkan penderitaan makhluk lain dan pengetahuannya tentang khasiat tumbuhan, Okuninushi menunjukkan sifat welas asih yang jauh melampaui kekuatan fisik, sebuah kebajikan yang akan menjadi inti dari seluruh kisahnya di kemudian hari.''',
        bodyEn: '''When Okuninushi finally arrived at that place, far behind the others because he carried all his brothers' baggage, he found the hare still weeping in pain on the shore. Full of compassion, he asked what had happened, and the hare told him its entire story, including the cruel advice the eighty brothers had given earlier. Okuninushi immediately offered the true remedy: he told the hare to go to the mouth of the nearest river, wash itself in fresh water to cleanse away the salt, then roll in the pollen of the kama reeds (cattails), which would cling to its wounds and heal them. The hare followed these instructions carefully, and at once its fur was restored perfectly as before. Through his patience in listening to another creature's suffering and his knowledge of the healing properties of plants, Okuninushi displayed a compassion far surpassing mere physical strength, a virtue that would become the very core of his later story.''',
