  MythStory(
    id: 'japanese-ninigi-descent',
    mythology: 'Japanese',
    icon: '🌾',
    title: 'Turunnya Ninigi ke Bumi',
    titleEn: 'The Descent of Ninigi',
    summary: 'Setelah Izumo diserahkan kepada para dewa langit, Amaterasu mengutus cucunya Ninigi turun ke Gunung Takachiho membawa Tiga Pusaka Suci, dan pilihannya menikahi Konohanasakuya-hime menjadi asal mula umur pendek garis kaisar.',
    summaryEn: 'After Izumo is ceded to the heavenly gods, Amaterasu sends her grandson Ninigi down to Mount Takachiho bearing the Three Sacred Treasures, and his choice to marry Konohanasakuya-hime becomes the origin of the imperial line\'s mortal, shortened lifespan.',
    timeline: 'Zaman Para Dewa · Awal Garis Kaisar',
    timelineEn: 'Age of the Gods · Origin of the Imperial Line',
    chapters: [
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Penyerahan Tanah Izumo',
        headingEn: 'The Ceding of the Land of Izumo',
        body: '''Setelah Okuninushi membangun dan menata tanah Izumo hingga menjadi negeri yang makmur, Amaterasu, dewi matahari dan penguasa Takamagahara (Dataran Tinggi Surga), memutuskan bahwa bumi seharusnya diperintah oleh keturunan langsungnya sendiri. Ia mengutus beberapa dewa berturut-turut untuk membujuk Okuninushi menyerahkan kekuasaannya, namun sebagian utusan itu justru berkhianat dan tinggal di bumi. Akhirnya dua dewa perkasa, Takemikazuchi dan Futsunushi, dikirim untuk berunding secara langsung. Setelah putra Okuninushi, Takeminakata, dikalahkan dalam adu kekuatan dan melarikan diri hingga ke Suwa, Okuninushi pun setuju menyerahkan tanahnya dengan satu syarat: sebuah kuil megah, yakni Izumo Taisha, harus dibangun untuk memujanya selamanya. Peristiwa yang dikenal sebagai kuniyuzuri (penyerahan tanah) ini menandai berakhirnya era dewa-dewa duniawi Izumo dan membuka jalan bagi turunnya keturunan langit ke bumi.''',
        bodyEn: '''After Okuninushi had built and ordered the land of Izumo into a prosperous realm, Amaterasu, the sun goddess and ruler of Takamagahara, the High Plain of Heaven, decided that the earth should be governed by her own direct descendants. She sent several gods in succession to persuade Okuninushi to surrender his rule, but some of these envoys instead betrayed her and settled on earth themselves. Finally two mighty gods, Takemikazuchi and Futsunushi, were dispatched to negotiate directly. After Okuninushi's son, Takeminakata, was defeated in a contest of strength and fled all the way to Suwa, Okuninushi agreed to relinquish his land on one condition: that a magnificent shrine, Izumo Taisha, be built to honor him forever. This event, known as kuniyuzuri, the ceding of the land, marked the end of the age of Izumo's earthly gods and opened the way for the descent of the heavenly lineage to earth.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Perintah Amaterasu dan Tiga Pusaka Suci',
        headingEn: 'Amaterasu\'s Decree and the Three Sacred Treasures',
        body: '''Dengan tanah telah diserahkan, Amaterasu memerintahkan cucunya sendiri, Ninigi-no-Mikoto, putra dari putranya Ame-no-Oshihomimi, untuk turun ke bumi dan memerintah sebagai penguasa sah. Sebagai lambang kekuasaan dan legitimasi ilahi, Amaterasu menganugerahkan kepada Ninigi Tiga Pusaka Suci (Sanshu no Jingi): cermin Yata-no-Kagami yang pernah memancing Amaterasu keluar dari gua langit, pedang Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi yang ditemukan Susanoo di dalam tubuh naga berkepala delapan Yamata-no-Orochi, dan permata Yasakani-no-Magatama yang melambangkan kebajikan. Ketiga pusaka ini menjadi bukti sah bahwa kekuasaan Ninigi berasal langsung dari Takamagahara, sekaligus simbol tiga kebajikan kaisar: kebijaksanaan (cermin), keberanian (pedang), dan kemurahan hati (permata). Amaterasu juga berpesan bahwa negeri yang akan diperintah keturunannya akan makmur selama padi dan gandum tumbuh subur di sana, sebuah janji yang mengikat garis kaisar dengan kesuburan tanah Jepang itu sendiri.''',
        bodyEn: '''With the land now ceded, Amaterasu commanded her own grandson, Ninigi-no-Mikoto, son of her son Ame-no-Oshihomimi, to descend to earth and rule as its rightful sovereign. As a symbol of authority and divine legitimacy, Amaterasu bestowed upon Ninigi the Three Sacred Treasures (Sanshu no Jingi): the mirror Yata-no-Kagami, which had once lured Amaterasu out of the heavenly cave, the sword Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi, found by Susanoo inside the body of the eight-headed dragon Yamata-no-Orochi, and the jewel Yasakani-no-Magatama, symbol of virtue. These three treasures served as proof that Ninigi's authority came directly from Takamagahara, and together they represented the three imperial virtues: wisdom (the mirror), courage (the sword), and benevolence (the jewel). Amaterasu further decreed that the land her descendants would rule would prosper for as long as rice and grain grew abundantly there, a promise binding the imperial line to the very fertility of the land of Japan itself.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Turun ke Gunung Takachiho',
        headingEn: 'The Descent to Mount Takachiho',
        body: '''Ninigi turun dari Takamagahara diiringi rombongan dewa pengiring, termasuk Ame-no-Uzume, dewi tarian yang pernah memancing Amaterasu keluar dari gua, dan Sarutahiko-no-Kami, dewa berhidung panjang penunjuk jalan yang menyambutnya di persimpangan delapan jalan langit dan bumi. Rombongan itu turun menembus awan hingga tiba di puncak Gunung Takachiho di wilayah Hyuga, sebuah puncak berkabut di Kyushu yang dipilih karena keindahannya menghadap lautan dan daratan subur. Berdiri di puncak itu, Ninigi memandang ke segala penjuru dan menyatakan bahwa tempat itu menghadap Korea di satu sisi, disinari matahari pagi dan senja dengan sempurna, sehingga ia memutuskan untuk mendirikan istananya di sana. Peristiwa turunnya sang cucu dewa ini dikenal sebagai tenson korin, "turunnya keturunan surgawi", sebuah momen sakral yang menjadi titik awal keberadaan fisik keturunan Amaterasu di bumi manusia.''',
        bodyEn: '''Ninigi descended from Takamagahara accompanied by a retinue of attendant gods, including Ame-no-Uzume, the goddess of dance who had once lured Amaterasu from her cave, and Sarutahiko-no-Kami, the long-nosed guide deity who met them at the crossing of the eight roads between heaven and earth. The procession descended through the clouds until it reached the summit of Mount Takachiho in the region of Hyuga, a mist-covered peak in Kyushu chosen for its beauty, overlooking both sea and fertile land. Standing atop the peak, Ninigi surveyed the land in every direction and declared that the place faced Korea on one side and was perfectly lit by the morning and evening sun, and so he decided to build his palace there. This descent of the divine grandson became known as tenson korin, the "descent of the heavenly grandchild," a sacred moment marking the beginning of Amaterasu's lineage's physical presence on the human earth.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Pilihan antara Batu dan Bunga',
        headingEn: 'The Choice Between Stone and Blossom',
        body: '''Di kaki gunung, Ninigi bertemu dengan Konohanasakuya-hime, putri jelita dewa gunung Oyamatsumi, dan seketika jatuh cinta lalu meminangnya. Oyamatsumi, dengan bangga, mengirimkan bukan hanya Konohanasakuya-hime tetapi juga kakaknya, Iwanaga-hime, sang "putri batu karang", sebagai istri kedua bagi Ninigi, berharap kedua putrinya dapat mempersembahkan berkah yang berbeda: Iwanaga-hime melambangkan keabadian dan ketahanan sekeras batu, sementara Konohanasakuya-hime melambangkan kesuburan dan keindahan secepat bunga sakura mekar. Namun Ninigi, karena Iwanaga-hime dianggapnya tidak cantik, menolak dan mengembalikannya kepada ayahnya, hanya menerima Konohanasakuya-hime. Oyamatsumi yang kecewa dan malu memperingatkan bahwa keputusan itu akan membawa akibat besar: seandainya Ninigi menerima kedua putrinya, keturunannya akan hidup abadi bagai batu; namun karena hanya memilih bunga, umur keturunannya kelak akan singkat dan rapuh seperti kelopak sakura yang gugur, sebuah kutukan yang menjelaskan mengapa para kaisar Jepang, meski berdarah ilahi, tetap fana.''',
        bodyEn: '''At the foot of the mountain, Ninigi met Konohanasakuya-hime, the beautiful daughter of the mountain god Oyamatsumi, and instantly fell in love and proposed marriage. Oyamatsumi, proudly, sent not only Konohanasakuya-hime but also her elder sister, Iwanaga-hime, the "princess of enduring rocks," as a second bride for Ninigi, hoping his two daughters might grant different blessings: Iwanaga-hime symbolizing eternity and endurance as hard as stone, while Konohanasakuya-hime symbolized fertility and beauty as fleeting as blossoming cherry flowers. But Ninigi, finding Iwanaga-hime unattractive, refused her and sent her back to her father, accepting only Konohanasakuya-hime. Oyamatsumi, disappointed and ashamed, warned that this choice would carry grave consequences: had Ninigi accepted both daughters, his descendants would have lived eternally like stone; but having chosen only the blossom, his lineage's lives would thereafter be as short and fragile as falling cherry petals, a curse explaining why Japan's emperors, though of divine blood, remain mortal.''',
      ),
      StoryChapter(
        heading: 'Penutup',
        headingEn: 'Closing',
        body: '''Pernikahan Ninigi dan Konohanasakuya-hime kelak diuji lebih jauh ketika sang putri hamil hanya dalam satu malam bersama, memicu kecurigaan Ninigi bahwa anak itu bukan miliknya. Untuk membuktikan kesuciannya, Konohanasakuya-hime memasuki gubuk tanpa pintu yang sengaja dibakarnya sendiri, bersumpah bahwa jika anak-anaknya bukan keturunan dewa, mereka akan binasa dalam api; ketiga putranya lahir selamat tanpa cedera di tengah kobaran itu, salah satunya kelak menjadi kakek dari Jimmu, kaisar pertama Jepang menurut tradisi. Dari puncak Takachiho hingga kelahiran ajaib di tengah api itulah garis keturunan kaisar Jepang, yang dipercaya tak terputus hingga masa kini, bermula. Kisah turunnya Ninigi menjadi fondasi mitologis bagi legitimasi Tenno, penguasa Jepang, sebagai keturunan langsung dewi matahari Amaterasu.''',
        bodyEn: '''The marriage of Ninigi and Konohanasakuya-hime would later be tested further when the princess became pregnant after only a single night together, arousing Ninigi's suspicion that the child was not his own. To prove her purity, Konohanasakuya-hime entered a doorless hut she deliberately set ablaze herself, vowing that if her children were not truly divine, they would perish in the flames; all three of her sons were born unharmed amid the fire, one of whom would later become the grandfather of Jimmu, traditionally regarded as Japan's first emperor. From the summit of Takachiho to that miraculous birth amid the flames, the imperial line of Japan, believed unbroken to this very day, had its beginning. The story of Ninigi's descent became the mythological foundation for the legitimacy of the Tenno, Japan's sovereign, as a direct descendant of the sun goddess Amaterasu.''',
      ),
    ],
